entry.title: Thread safety annotations for thread_safe_statics.cpp (& rest of MS CRT?)
entry.content:
thread_safe_statics.cpp in the Microsoft CRT is used to do threadsafe static initialization, e.g. for function-local statics. In bug 325589473 Chrome's main thread deadlocked due to reentrance during threadsafe static init. If the code here had been annotated with thread safety annotations, we might have caught this earlier, e.g. at compile time.
base/thread_annotations.h define the macros Chrome uses. I assume Microsoft would want to use macros also, since they'd want SAL annotations when compiled with msvc, and Clang annotations with Clang.
Alison, not sure of the right contact point at Microsoft for this. Can you triage?

entry.title: Deleting a cookie removes the current cookie selection
entry.content:
Chrome Version : 123.0.6312.105 (Official Build) (64-bit) OS : Debian Bookworm
What steps will reproduce the problem? 1. Open the Application panel and select a cookie for some subdomain 2. Press Del to delete the cookie.
What is the expected result? The cookie gets deleted and another one (next to it) gets selected, so that multiple cookies can get deleted by hitting Del multiple times in succession.
What happens instead? The cookie gets deleted and another one does not get selected, that is, the selection is gone.
This is a regression.

entry.title: Chromium uses invalid xdg-activation token
entry.content:
Since 124, chromium windows under wayland are no longer activated (focused) when `chromium <url>` is executed and the site is opened in an existing window. Instead of using a valid xdg-activation token, chromium uses a token that is unknown to the compositor. For example
``` java-1742680-desk-/usr/bin/chromium-2_TIME0 ```
This is a regression. It worked in 123.

entry.title: Request update due to `HttpsUpgrades` feature are not paused by Fetch interception
entry.content:
Chrome introduces the `HttpsUpgrades` feature https://chromestatus.com/feature/6056181032812544. The such update request are reported by the CDP Network domain but remain not intercepted by the Fetch domain. This creates an issue that such request can't intercepted and also that these there is no way to differentiate them from a normal request.
Which from our understanding is happening around https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:net/url_request/url_request_job.cc;l=181;drc=11c6fee8868a670b11ae04cf5649f7805f6cc16a https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:chrome/browser/ssl/https_upgrades_interceptor.h;drc=fe132eeb21687c455d695d6af346f15454828d01
A link to the CDP logs from Puppeteer that show the behavior https://gist.github.com/Lightning00Blade/e88e7b7aa8cd332a8fc0ee5e6fda57db Line 18 and Line 21 have the event, but only a single `Fetch.requestPaused` is emitted after. Related Puppeteer issue

entry.title: Cancel array buffer sweeping instead of finalizing (when possible)
entry.content:
The array buffer sweeper is using a cancelable task for background sweeping. This task cannot be interrupted and can only be cancelled if it hasn't already started.
In some cases, we could cancel array buffer sweeping instead of finishing it prior to starting a new GC (specifically, when we know all array buffer are promoted).
Before we can cancel sweeping, we need to be able interrupt a running array buffer sweeping task. To do end, we will refactor the array buffer sweeper to use the jobs api and yield when needed.
